# Introduction

Indian agriculture is highly dependent on monsoon rainfall, which contributes nearly 70–80% of the country’s annual precipitation. The monsoon season, occurring from June to September, plays a critical role in determining agricultural productivity, cropping patterns, and rural livelihoods.

However, monsoon rainfall in India is highly variable and often irregular. Delayed monsoons can lead to drought conditions, while excessive rainfall can cause floods, both of which negatively impact crop production.

This study focuses on understanding the relationship between monsoon variability and agricultural productivity (rice and wheat yields) in India from 1980 to 2020. The study uses statistical methods to analyse how rainfall fluctuations influence long-term agricultural trends.
